It is expected that the *Total Duration* field on displaying the detail test results for a test suite would be taken directly from the report xml. This screen seems to be calculating the value instead :(. 

{code:xml}
<testsuite time='25.301' failures='0' errors='0' skipped='0' tests='18' name='test'>
{code} 
{noformat}
Total Duration: 66.874 seconds
{noformat}

While generally they will match for JUnit generated reports, other test tools produce JUnit-style reports for various testing scenarios (not unit tests) and one of the primary reasons is to integrate well into CI and other tools. In these cases you should rely on the tool produced value from xml instead of calculating it yourself. Specifically, the calculation is not correct if multiple testcases are run concurrently in a test suite.

On a side note, it is nice that Bamboo refers to *Tests* in general and not specifically unit tests, although there is still a few cases were *unit test* term is used like on this detail display.

We enforce a non-null constraint on the USER_NAME column, if username is not specified during loging:
{code}
2010-07-19 12:50:00,469 INFO [7373191@qtp-16554308-202] [DefaultAuthenticator] login : '' does not exist and cannot be authenticated.
{code}

Bamboo throws a SQL error, as Oracle interprets empty strings as NULL:
{code}
2010-07-19 12:50:00,479 ERROR [7373191@qtp-16554308-202] [FiveOhOh] 500 Exception was thrown.
org.springframework.dao.DataIntegrityViolationException: Hibernate operation: Could not execute JDBC batch update; SQL []; ORA-01400: cannot insert NULL into ("BAMBOO"."AUTH_ATTEMPT_INFO"."USER_NAME")
; nested exception is java.sql.BatchUpdateException: ORA-01400: cannot insert NULL into ("BAMBOO"."AUTH_ATTEMPT_INFO"."USER_NAME")
{code}

Bamboo checks license expiry against the current date, instead of the release date for the Bamboo version:

{code}
    public boolean isMaintenanceExpired()
    {
        return maintenanceExpiryDate != null && maintenanceExpiryDate.compareTo(new Date()) < 0;
    }
{code}
Our license are meant to be perpetual, and customers should be able to run a Bamboo version if it was released before the expiry date!

The cron expression:
{code}
* */5 * * * *
{code}

is rejected, while 

{code}
* */5 * ? * *
{code}

Is accepted...

